89
00:04:13,724 --> 00:04:14,744
and they were,

90
00:04:15,815 --> 00:04:17,937
Michael Jackson's Moonwalker on Sega,

91
00:04:17,937 --> 00:04:21,539
and the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles game on NES.

92
00:04:21,539 --> 00:04:23,981
And when I was seven, my family had just immigrated

93
00:04:23,981 --> 00:04:25,922
to Canada for about a couple years,

94
00:04:25,922 --> 00:04:28,064
and I'm the youngest of a really big family.

95
00:04:28,064 --> 00:04:29,344
So I was kind of left alone.

96
00:04:31,579 --> 00:04:33,200
while they were teaching themselves English,

97
00:04:33,200 --> 00:04:34,920
I was kind of left alone because like,

98
00:04:34,920 --> 00:04:35,940
it's when you're five,

99
00:04:35,940 --> 00:04:39,761
it's pretty easy to pick up another language.

100
00:04:39,761 --> 00:04:42,762
So I had all these floppy disks that were like,

101
00:04:42,762 --> 00:04:44,982
vocabulary games and math games in addition,

102
00:04:44,982 --> 00:04:47,963
but then I found another floppy disk that had Doom 2.

103
00:04:47,963 --> 00:04:51,404
And that's kind of when I became a gamer for,

104
00:04:51,404 --> 00:04:52,684
and I knew that this is something that I wanted to do

105
00:04:52,684 --> 00:04:55,705
for the rest of my life.

106
00:04:55,705 --> 00:04:58,105
But when it came to like an academic and professional life,

107
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:00,642
I didn't get into games right away.

108
00:05:00,642 --> 00:05:03,304
So at first I studied political science and criminology.

109
00:05:03,304 --> 00:05:07,888
And I say it's because I wanted to be a human rights lawyer,

110
00:05:07,888 --> 00:05:10,810
but I think I just wanted a sexy, crime-fighting forensics

111
00:05:10,810 --> 00:05:11,091
job.

112
00:05:11,091 --> 00:05:15,995
And fortunately, that dream dissipated.

113
00:05:15,995 --> 00:05:20,038
But unfortunately, I took into film studies and philosophy,

114
00:05:20,038 --> 00:05:23,881
so I wanted to be unemployed for the rest of my life.

115
00:05:23,881 --> 00:05:26,083
But this is really the point where

116
00:05:27,411 --> 00:05:32,354
I started looking at media and like representation in media

117
00:05:32,354 --> 00:05:33,515
and race relations in media

118
00:05:33,515 --> 00:05:37,298
and how powerful of a tool it can be.

119
00:05:37,298 --> 00:05:39,699
I specialize specifically in black exploitation cinema

120
00:05:39,699 --> 00:05:41,741
and Palestinian cinema.

121
00:05:41,741 --> 00:05:44,002
And this is where a lot of my interests

122
00:05:44,002 --> 00:05:46,083
in terms of like, okay, the media that we have

123
00:05:46,083 --> 00:05:46,984
is not just entertainment,

124
00:05:46,984 --> 00:05:49,826
it could be something really meaningful and valuable.

125
00:05:49,826 --> 00:05:54,068
And not just because we see diverse characters in something,

126
00:05:54,068 --> 00:05:55,349
but they're actually,

127
00:05:55,349 --> 00:05:55,429
the

128
00:05:56,478 --> 00:05:58,799
Films in black exploitation in Palestinian cinema

129
00:05:58,799 --> 00:06:00,520
are made by those people.

130
00:06:00,520 --> 00:06:04,702
So it's very much an introspective externalization.

131
00:06:04,702 --> 00:06:05,802
So I then moved to Toronto.

132
00:06:05,802 --> 00:06:10,684
I pursued my master's in, again, nothing game related.

133
00:06:10,684 --> 00:06:12,745
It was film and photographic preservation.

134
00:06:12,745 --> 00:06:16,047
And strangely, this is actually

135
00:06:16,047 --> 00:06:18,128
where my career in games began.

136
00:06:18,128 --> 00:06:21,129
So Toronto has an awesome indie game scene.

137
00:06:21,129 --> 00:06:23,190
And it was there that I stumbled upon

138
00:06:23,522 --> 00:06:24,783
Dane's making games and they're like all here,

139
00:06:24,783 --> 00:06:26,664
like dispersed throughout.

140
00:06:26,664 --> 00:06:29,125
So if you see them, you should say hello to them

141
00:06:29,125 --> 00:06:30,306
and find out what they're working on.

142
00:06:30,306 --> 00:06:32,507
They're a great initiative.

143
00:06:32,507 --> 00:06:35,228
It's a non-profit to support women and non-binary folks

144
00:06:35,228 --> 00:06:38,450
to make games and provide them with mentorship

145
00:06:38,450 --> 00:06:41,792
and accessible tools, particularly open source tools.

146
00:06:41,792 --> 00:06:45,914
And this blew my mind because up until this point,

147
00:06:45,914 --> 00:06:48,535
I hadn't really seen people make games

148
00:06:48,535 --> 00:06:50,396
when they didn't have technical backgrounds.

149
00:06:51,486 --> 00:06:54,969
one of the sort of myths about the tech industry

150
00:06:54,969 --> 00:06:56,450
is that you have to be a programmer

151
00:06:56,450 --> 00:06:59,092
or you have to be a computer scientist to make it big

152
00:06:59,092 --> 00:07:01,273
and that's not true.

153
00:07:01,273 --> 00:07:06,677
And this is where DMG really started to shape a lot

154
00:07:06,677 --> 00:07:07,398
of how I felt about game making.

155
00:07:07,398 --> 00:07:10,120
And really up until this point in my life,

156
00:07:10,120 --> 00:07:12,641
I never really like played indie games.

157
00:07:12,641 --> 00:07:15,023
It was mostly AAA games and the indie games

158
00:07:15,023 --> 00:07:16,284
were ones that were on console.

159
00:07:16,284 --> 00:07:17,105
It's not kind of like.

160
00:07:17,448 --> 00:07:19,409
how today there's a lot of, you know,

161
00:07:19,409 --> 00:07:21,090
there are marketplaces on consoles

162
00:07:21,090 --> 00:07:22,290
where there's tons of indie games.

163
00:07:22,290 --> 00:07:24,111
This was before that was happening.

164
00:07:24,111 --> 00:07:26,632
So this was a really cool experience.

165
00:07:26,632 --> 00:07:28,152
I volunteered with them for a couple of years

166
00:07:28,152 --> 00:07:30,513
and then shortly after that,

167
00:07:30,513 --> 00:07:31,834
I sat on their board of directors.

168
00:07:31,834 --> 00:07:35,575
And this is where I seriously started thinking about

169
00:07:35,575 --> 00:07:38,296
accessible game making and how many stories

170
00:07:38,296 --> 00:07:40,697
that aren't represented in blockbuster games

171
00:07:40,697 --> 00:07:43,778
that can be mobilized in, like, through indie game making.

172
00:07:45,906 --> 00:07:47,806
One of my favorite highlights was Indigicaid.

173
00:07:47,806 --> 00:07:50,327
And it's a collaboration between DMG

174
00:07:50,327 --> 00:07:51,727
and the Indigenous Routes Collective

175
00:07:51,727 --> 00:07:54,147
to teach a group of six indigenous girls and women

176
00:07:54,147 --> 00:07:55,808
between the age of 13 to 24

177
00:07:55,808 --> 00:07:59,108
on how to make their first video game from scratch.

178
00:07:59,108 --> 00:08:01,469
And this was really eye-opening for me.

179
00:08:01,469 --> 00:08:04,869
It was eye-opening to watch this group

180
00:08:04,869 --> 00:08:06,970
give voice to their experiences and imaginations

181
00:08:06,970 --> 00:08:09,970
in a way that is entirely new to them.

182
00:08:09,970 --> 00:08:11,710
They were artists in different ways,

183
00:08:11,710 --> 00:08:12,651
but this is the first time

184
00:08:12,651 --> 00:08:14,191
that they're using game-making tools.

185
00:08:15,184 --> 00:08:17,085
And like, game making is really intimidating.

186
00:08:17,085 --> 00:08:19,546
Even when you know what you're doing,

187
00:08:19,546 --> 00:08:21,666
it's an overwhelming career choice to get into.

188
00:08:21,666 --> 00:08:25,768
And so mentoring just one of the women

189
00:08:25,768 --> 00:08:27,048
to help her create her story,

190
00:08:27,048 --> 00:08:30,549
that gave me a lot of hope for the future

191
00:08:30,549 --> 00:08:32,170
of girls and women of color in games.

192
00:08:32,170 --> 00:08:34,811
So at this point in my career,

193
00:08:34,811 --> 00:08:36,871
I considered dropping out of grad school.

194
00:08:36,871 --> 00:08:39,812
And I didn't, and there's like one reason

195
00:08:39,812 --> 00:08:41,533
I feel like that I didn't drop out of grad school.

196
00:08:42,248 --> 00:08:48,093
My master's thesis was so not what photo historians wanted to talk about or deal with that they

197
00:08:48,093 --> 00:08:50,354
buddied me up with a game studies professor.

198
00:08:50,354 --> 00:08:58,920
So we just spent most of our time talking about Resident Evil and he was just like,

199
00:08:58,920 --> 00:09:00,141
yeah, submit it whenever you're ready.

200
00:09:00,141 --> 00:09:00,261
Sweet.

201
00:09:00,261 --> 00:09:00,542
So one point.

202
00:09:00,542 --> 00:09:06,666
But the changes really started in terms of the changes in how I thought about diverse

203
00:09:06,666 --> 00:09:09,748
communities and indie game making.

204
00:09:10,615 --> 00:09:12,997
it really started to foster when I worked

205
00:09:12,997 --> 00:09:14,919
in community management for a mobile game studio

206
00:09:14,919 --> 00:09:16,500
called Yukon.

