00:23:24,235 --> 00:23:26,536
especially since in the games and tech industry specifically

519
00:23:26,536 --> 00:23:29,098
it was kind of exploding all of a sudden.

520
00:23:29,098 --> 00:23:30,559
Everybody wanted to talk about it.

521
00:23:30,559 --> 00:23:33,241
But this is the first time somebody who's me

522
00:23:33,241 --> 00:23:35,403
was like hired to work on this full time

523
00:23:35,403 --> 00:23:36,824
and actually develop a solution.

524
00:23:38,598 --> 00:23:43,161
So, small panic attack over after reading that article,

525
00:23:43,161 --> 00:23:46,483
I realized that these reactions make complete sense.

526
00:23:46,483 --> 00:23:49,605
These reactions to policies and trainings

527
00:23:49,605 --> 00:23:52,327
and sort of like sensitivity training sessions,

528
00:23:52,327 --> 00:23:54,929
they make sense.

529
00:23:54,929 --> 00:23:58,151
And the reason I feel it's because

530
00:23:58,151 --> 00:24:00,132
people don't change because of company policy.

531
00:24:00,132 --> 00:24:00,613
I feel like

532
00:24:01,066 --> 00:24:02,728
There are some folks in here who work in HR

533
00:24:02,728 --> 00:24:05,211
can probably attest to that, where it's like,

534
00:24:05,211 --> 00:24:06,333
yeah, if you put up a policy,

535
00:24:06,333 --> 00:24:08,776
it's not like everybody's going to be suddenly inspired

536
00:24:08,776 --> 00:24:10,518
to change all of the behaviors

537
00:24:10,518 --> 00:24:12,000
that are included with that policy.

538
00:24:13,782 --> 00:24:16,964
focusing on policies doesn't actually address

539
00:24:16,964 --> 00:24:19,126
the root cause of exclusionary behavior.

540
00:24:19,126 --> 00:24:21,607
And diversity policies especially,

541
00:24:21,607 --> 00:24:23,729
they can create an illusion that's not real.

542
00:24:23,729 --> 00:24:25,530
They can create an illusion that different people

543
00:24:25,530 --> 00:24:28,412
are treated, that they're unfairly rewarded

544
00:24:28,412 --> 00:24:29,873
or unfairly treated or that they're

545
00:24:29,873 --> 00:24:31,094
too fairly treated and rewarded.

546
00:24:31,094 --> 00:24:33,756
And that causes a lot of tension and resentment internally.

547
00:24:33,756 --> 00:24:36,077
So we're pretty quick to think of tactics like policies

548
00:24:43,376 --> 00:24:45,917
or trainings to solve D&I issues.

549
00:24:45,917 --> 00:24:48,138
But without understanding what it is that we're aiming for

550
00:24:48,138 --> 00:24:49,219
or trying to learn or trying to change,

551
00:24:49,219 --> 00:24:50,059
a lot of damage can be unintentionally done

552
00:24:50,059 --> 00:24:51,099
because of distrust or misperceptions.

553
00:24:51,099 --> 00:24:52,040
So there are a couple of key values

554
00:24:52,040 --> 00:24:53,140
that I wanted to share today

555
00:24:53,140 --> 00:24:54,341
that I found particularly helpful for my own growth

556
00:24:54,341 --> 00:24:55,241
as a diversity inclusion manager.

557
00:25:07,597 --> 00:25:10,758
And my hypothesis is that hopefully what I share

558
00:25:10,758 --> 00:25:12,679
can help programs be successful and meaningful

559
00:25:12,679 --> 00:25:13,799
and have lasting effect.

560
00:25:13,799 --> 00:25:15,940
So it's not about not having programs.

561
00:25:15,940 --> 00:25:17,321
It's not about not having policies.

562
00:25:17,321 --> 00:25:20,162
It's about understanding why you're doing them.

563
00:25:20,162 --> 00:25:22,403
So as a D&I manager, I'm obviously, I'm for the people.

564
00:25:22,403 --> 00:25:26,185
And that probably sounds super obvious,

565
00:25:26,185 --> 00:25:29,486
but it's all people.

566
00:25:29,486 --> 00:25:32,868
Everybody wants to talk to the diversity inclusion manager

567
00:25:32,868 --> 00:25:34,329
because we all have different experiences

568
00:25:34,329 --> 00:25:36,890
that we believe are valuable to our teams.

569
00:25:38,613 --> 00:25:40,675
But there was this light bulb moment

570
00:25:40,675 --> 00:25:43,397
that where I had to pivot how I engaged with everyone,

571
00:25:43,397 --> 00:25:45,259
not just everybody at my work,

572
00:25:45,259 --> 00:25:47,861
but also in the industry as well.

573
00:25:47,861 --> 00:25:51,444
This is the part of the larger sort of D&I discourse

574
00:25:51,444 --> 00:25:54,406
that I feel like a lot of professionals don't stress

575
00:25:54,406 --> 00:25:56,708
and it can be really easy to take for granted.

576
00:25:58,212 --> 00:26:01,654
Because I came in thinking like, all right, I'm an advocate.

577
00:26:01,654 --> 00:26:03,435
I'm going to find all the underrepresented groups.

578
00:26:03,435 --> 00:26:05,397
I'm going to peer them out.

579
00:26:05,397 --> 00:26:07,878
And I'm going to create programs and initiatives

580
00:26:07,878 --> 00:26:08,618
based on what they need.

581
00:26:08,618 --> 00:26:11,940
And that sounds like a great thing to do.

582
00:26:11,940 --> 00:26:12,941
Because it's not a bad thing to do.

583
00:26:12,941 --> 00:26:16,863
That's not a negative solution.

584
00:26:16,863 --> 00:26:20,466
But without taking the time to understand the majority groups

585
00:26:20,466 --> 00:26:23,047
that these underrepresented groups are collaborating

586
00:26:23,047 --> 00:26:26,309
with on a daily basis and working with on a daily basis.

587
00:26:26,730 --> 00:26:40,795
Programs and trainings and so forth that are targeting the majority groups will probably feel a little bit like this

588
00:26:40,795 --> 00:26:43,316
Gentle persuasion

589
00:26:43,316 --> 00:26:48,218
So especially with the current political climate

590
00:26:48,218 --> 00:26:53,220
Building bridges to each other now is more crucial than ever

591
00:26:53,220 --> 00:26:54,200
So NPR published an article

592
00:26:54,815 --> 00:26:57,396
about how after the American election,

593
00:26:57,396 --> 00:27:00,558
there was this new version of us versus them,

594
00:27:00,558 --> 00:27:03,000
and where professional peacemakers,

595
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:05,802
who would be diversity managers,

596
00:27:05,802 --> 00:27:07,263
share some of the immediate challenges

597
00:27:07,263 --> 00:27:09,464
of a deeply divided country,

598
00:27:09,464 --> 00:27:12,086
like addressing the concerns of people

599
00:27:12,086 --> 00:27:14,007
usually thought of as privileged,

600
00:27:14,007 --> 00:27:17,169
or having to navigate a language minefield

601
00:27:17,169 --> 00:27:19,651
where the wrong word can ignite conflict.

602
00:27:20,463 --> 00:27:23,324
And speaking of my own personal experiences after the election,

603
00:27:23,324 --> 00:27:26,645
it was just like all of a sudden everybody on Facebook had an opinion

604
00:27:26,645 --> 00:27:28,186
and everybody wanted to tell you it.

605
00:27:28,186 --> 00:27:33,368
And there was just like threads of drama and blocking and freak outs.

606
00:27:33,368 --> 00:27:36,009
And it makes, like, there's a lot of anxiety right now.

607
00:27:36,009 --> 00:27:37,970
There is a lot of tension.

608
00:27:37,970 --> 00:27:40,071
And there's an uptick that, you know,

609
00:27:40,071 --> 00:27:42,192
I don't think a lot of people were expecting to see in 2017.

610
00:27:42,192 --> 00:27:45,553
We're seeing more division and resentment.

611
00:27:45,553 --> 00:27:48,074
It's leading to isolation.

612
00:27:48,074 --> 00:27:49,635
It's resorting to groupthink.

613
00:27:51,082 --> 00:27:53,263
and we're starting to fear the unknown.

614
00:27:53,263 --> 00:27:56,425
And there's a restlessness and a whirlwind of breaking news.

615
00:27:56,425 --> 00:28:00,607
Like every day, something new is happening and it's awful.

616
00:28:00,607 --> 00:28:02,668
And it's like moving leaders and managers

617
00:28:02,668 --> 00:28:04,009
to sort of have to realize,

618
00:28:04,009 --> 00:28:06,210
how do I keep the calm internally?

619
00:28:06,210 --> 00:28:09,292
And how do I like call for everybody to unite?

620
00:28:11,787 --> 00:28:14,528
And there's also growing research on how social media

621
00:28:14,528 --> 00:28:16,528
is disrupting the way that we communicate with each other

622
00:28:16,528 --> 00:28:19,569
about specifically political issues.

623
00:28:19,569 --> 00:28:22,049
And I've been seeing a lot of parallels personally

624
00:28:22,049 --> 00:28:26,810
with how that's been specifically

625
00:28:26,810 --> 00:28:29,091
affecting the D&I conversation.

626
00:28:29,091 --> 00:28:31,291
And if we don't address the sort of disconnect

627
00:28:31,291 --> 00:28:33,732
that's happening between how people look at each other

628
00:28:33,732 --> 00:28:35,872
politically and how people look at each other,

629
00:28:35,872 --> 00:28:38,313
how people communicate to each other on social media,

630
00:28:38,313 --> 00:28:40,193
I feel like we're ignoring a vital piece of the puzzle.

631
00:28:41,490 --> 00:28:45,732
And it's most recently played an unprecedented role

632
00:28:45,732 --> 00:28:48,973
in the American election and in the current administration.

633
00:28:48,973 --> 00:28:52,294
Like in January, we saw press secretary Sean Spicer,

634
00:28:52,294 --> 00:28:55,236
the Spice Man, hold up a printed tweet

635
00:28:55,236 --> 00:28:57,436
to address it at an actual press conference.

636
00:28:57,436 --> 00:28:58,437
Like at the rate that we're going,

637
00:28:58,437 --> 00:29:01,638
we're gonna see political tweets in textbooks.

638
00:29:01,638 --> 00:29:03,479
It's gonna be part of language.

639
00:29:05,295 --> 00:29:07,175
And like, listen, like as a millennial,

640
00:29:07,175 --> 00:29:09,516
I hate when people blame shit on social media,

641
00:29:09,516 --> 00:29:10,417
even though that's like low key

642
00:29:10,417 --> 00:29:12,118
what I'm trying to do right now.

643
00:29:12,118 --> 00:29:15,199
Because obviously like majority and minority tensions,

644
00:29:15,199 --> 00:29:17,960
like tensions between majority and minority groups,

645
00:29:17,960 --> 00:29:19,921
that's been around forever.

646
00:29:19,921 --> 00:29:25,443
But it's impossible to kind of ignore the growing impact

647
00:29:25,443 --> 00:29:28,284
of how online spaces directly frame

648
00:29:28,284 --> 00:29:30,545
and affect the conversations that we have in person

649
00:29:30,545 --> 00:29:31,906
as colleagues and as teammates.

650
00:29:33,470 --> 00:29:36,052
And we in the games industry especially,

651
00:29:36,052 --> 00:29:39,395
we have a lexicon that's built almost entirely

652
00:29:39,395 --> 00:29:41,337
on how we speak on the internet.

653
00:29:41,337 --> 00:29:43,479
Like we engage and care about an audience

654
00:29:43,479 --> 00:29:46,462
that knows the ins and outs of Reddit.

655
00:29:46,462 --> 00:29:48,384
They call us out for misusing memes

656
00:29:48,384 --> 00:29:51,327
and make sure to know that we're embarrassing ourselves.

657
00:29:51,327 --> 00:29:53,870
And they can easily out shit post all of us combined.

658
00:29:56,358 --> 00:29:58,900
In terms of social media affecting D&I in games,

659
00:29:58,900 --> 00:30:02,881
a number of initiatives and movements began as hashtags,

660
00:30:02,881 --> 00:30:04,642
and they sparked into something bigger.

661
00:30:04,642 --> 00:30:07,263
So this point and example,

662
00:30:07,263 --> 00:30:09,464
it began as hashtag one reason why,

663
00:30:09,464 --> 00:30:11,945
where a designer asked on Twitter

664
00:30:11,945 --> 00:30:13,866
why there are so few women creating games,

665
00:30:13,866 --> 00:30:16,227
and hundreds of women responded

666
00:30:16,227 --> 00:30:18,128
with anecdotes of sexism in the industry.

667
00:30:18,128 --> 00:30:20,208
And that evolved into hashtag one reason to be.

668
00:30:20,208 --> 00:30:21,689
And this was started,

669
00:30:25,066 --> 00:30:29,289
again on Twitter in response by narrative designer Rihanna Pratchett

670
00:30:29,289 --> 00:30:33,553
as to the positive reasons of why women are in games and why

671
00:30:33,553 --> 00:30:36,895
they should stay in games and why they should pursue their career

672
00:30:36,895 --> 00:30:41,599
in games. And this evolved into a series of GDC panels where women

673
00:30:41,599 --> 00:30:45,602
and minorities empower each other and inspire creators to make the industry

674
00:30:45,602 --> 00:30:48,925
more inclusive and to make us a better place.

675
00:30:48,925 --> 00:30:51,227
We also can't deny how

676
00:30:51,580 --> 00:30:55,823
social media field groups like GamerGate or the alt-right,

677
00:30:55,823 --> 00:30:58,364
and that have hugely impacted the conversations

678
00:30:58,364 --> 00:30:59,305
that we have every day about D&I.

679
00:30:59,305 --> 00:31:04,548
So what we're seeing is kind of like this wild evolution

680
00:31:04,548 --> 00:31:07,110
of not only media and how media is changing,

681
00:31:07,110 --> 00:31:08,771
but also our language with each other.

682
00:31:08,771 --> 00:31:12,233
Because on the one hand, you have free, accessible tools

683
00:31:12,233 --> 00:31:14,775
that are potential platforms and opportunities,

684
00:31:14,775 --> 00:31:17,897
which is a key part of mobilizing groups and ideas.

685
00:31:17,897 --> 00:31:18,417
And on the other hand,

686
00:31:21,732 --> 00:31:24,713
you have free accessible tools that are potential platforms

687
00:31:24,713 --> 00:31:28,174
and opportunities, which is a key part of mobilizing groups

688
00:31:28,174 --> 00:31:28,554
and ideas.

689
00:31:28,554 --> 00:31:31,255
So you have this potential for greater good

690
00:31:31,255 --> 00:31:34,116
and incredible change and this other potential

691
00:31:34,116 --> 00:31:35,637
of just raging dumpster fires.

692
00:31:35,637 --> 00:31:40,758
But really what I've noticed the most within this new lexicon

693
00:31:40,758 --> 00:31:44,219
is that we have a tendency to group people

694
00:31:44,219 --> 00:31:45,360
and shorthand them with labels

695
00:31:45,360 --> 00:31:46,860
that are loaded with assumptions.

696
00:31:48,149 --> 00:31:50,790
I've seen far too many conversations and I've like,

697
00:31:50,790 --> 00:31:52,550
I've had to catch myself from being part

698
00:31:52,550 --> 00:31:54,911
of those conversations where we devolve

699
00:31:54,911 --> 00:31:57,812
into a reductive dismissal of the other person

700
00:31:57,812 --> 00:31:59,993
and those reductive dismissals like appear

701
00:31:59,993 --> 00:32:01,553
on social media first.

702
00:32:01,553 --> 00:32:04,854
So like, you're a Bernie bro or you're a Feminazi

703
00:32:04,854 --> 00:32:06,815
or like you're a triggered snowflake.

704
00:32:06,815 --> 00:32:10,116
Like that all happens online but we actually use

705
00:32:10,116 --> 00:32:12,017
that sort of thinking too in person.

706
00:32:12,017 --> 00:32:15,298
And it's this quick clumping of.

707
00:32:16,545 --> 00:32:20,629
people to an online identity, it bleeds into the way that we talk to each other in real

708
00:32:20,629 --> 00:32:21,749
life.

709
00:32:21,749 --> 00:32:29,115
And even if we're more politically or philosophically aligned than not, I can't say that I'm entirely

710
00:32:29,115 --> 00:32:29,836
surprised.

711
00:32:29,836 --> 00:32:34,439
There are years of shorthanding and labeling and grouping that we've socially assigned

712
00:32:34,439 --> 00:32:37,622
each other that up until this point we're a very divided country.

713
00:32:37,622 --> 00:32:42,426
We're reducing each other to identities and affiliations and not considering much else.

714
00:32:43,624 --> 00:32:46,225
There is a great talk by Howard J. Ross,

715
00:32:46,225 --> 00:32:50,647
who he spoke about managing fear,

716
00:32:50,647 --> 00:32:52,808
managing bias in a time of fear.

717
00:32:52,808 --> 00:32:56,049
And it was all specifically about this kind of work,

718
00:32:56,049 --> 00:32:57,429
where it's like, how do you,

719
00:32:57,429 --> 00:32:58,810
people feel a lot of anxiety,

720
00:32:58,810 --> 00:33:01,131
where it's like, there the rise of sort of like,

721
00:33:01,131 --> 00:33:03,092
Black Lives Matter, and then people feeling like,

722
00:33:03,092 --> 00:33:04,632
do you mean like only Black Lives Matter,

723
00:33:04,632 --> 00:33:06,453
or like Black Lives Matter too?

724
00:33:06,453 --> 00:33:09,614
And then it kind of grows and grows,

725
00:33:09,614 --> 00:33:10,895
and especially with the election, you have,

726
00:33:11,395 --> 00:33:13,856
people reducing to each other to like,

727
00:33:13,856 --> 00:33:17,657
what do you believe in and what do you believe in

728
00:33:17,657 --> 00:33:18,617
versus anything else.

729
00:33:18,617 --> 00:33:20,017
We've lost a lot of nuance.

730
00:33:20,017 --> 00:33:23,678
So as a D&I manager, if I'm working for the people,

731
00:33:23,678 --> 00:33:25,139
I have to understand what makes them tick,

732
00:33:25,139 --> 00:33:29,340
what gives them pause, or else nothing that I give them

733
00:33:29,340 --> 00:33:32,241
is gonna address the root sort of cause

734
00:33:32,241 --> 00:33:34,402
of intolerance or exclusion.

735
00:33:35,592 --> 00:33:38,835
That means engaging with people I vehemently disagree with.

736
00:33:38,835 --> 00:33:40,436
And mind you, I'm not talking about trolls.

737
00:33:40,436 --> 00:33:42,357
I'm talking about people that you're working with,

738
00:33:42,357 --> 00:33:45,499
people in your industry, your peer group.

739
00:33:45,499 --> 00:33:48,321
If we believe that games are such a profound,

740
00:33:48,321 --> 00:33:49,863
core part of our lives,

741
00:33:49,863 --> 00:33:51,884
then we have to be working together on this.

742
00:33:53,050 --> 00:33:54,812
And it's not easy.

743
00:33:54,812 --> 00:33:56,793
Coming from, oops, sorry,

744
00:33:56,793 --> 00:33:58,634
just like brushed up against my mic,

745
00:33:58,634 --> 00:34:00,655
that probably didn't sound great.

746
00:34:00,655 --> 00:34:04,818
Coming from a non-profit that's rooted in social activism

747
00:34:04,818 --> 00:34:06,499
and moving directly into the industry

748
00:34:06,499 --> 00:34:08,621
where this is a conversation people are having

749
00:34:08,621 --> 00:34:11,923
for the first time, that made me have to stop

750
00:34:11,923 --> 00:34:14,665
and sort of refamiliarize myself with how I got into.

751
00:34:15,333 --> 00:34:20,575
this space and the sort of ways that I've stumbled along the way.

752
00:34:20,575 --> 00:34:25,177
And that can be super humbling and grounding and a reminder that we all have to start somewhere.

753
00:34:25,177 --> 00:34:30,779
So when we focus on building relationships, we're making an effort to find where bridges

754
00:34:30,779 --> 00:34:34,500
can connect, not watch them burn in the rearview mirror.

755
00:34:34,500 --> 00:34:36,381
And that's just one part of my hypothesis.

756
00:34:37,631 --> 00:34:39,291
You know, I'm not only invested in working with people

757
00:34:39,291 --> 00:34:43,132
who are heavily affected by diversity concerns,

758
00:34:43,132 --> 00:34:47,613
but also the skeptics and especially the people

759
00:34:47,613 --> 00:34:49,334
who are indifferent, the people who can kind of take it

760
00:34:49,334 --> 00:34:52,254
or leave it or never really had an opinion either way.

761
00:34:52,254 --> 00:34:57,136
And again, that might sound really painfully obvious,

762
00:34:57,136 --> 00:35:00,136
but like it's super blindsiding when that is not part

763
00:35:00,136 --> 00:35:03,997
of the core conversations that we have in D&I as a peer group.

764
00:35:05,329 --> 00:35:07,511
And another core part in navigating the space

765
00:35:07,511 --> 00:35:08,631
in a way that feels more authentic

766
00:35:08,631 --> 00:35:10,693
and is more meaningful to me

767
00:35:10,693 --> 00:35:13,054
is by fostering an organizational mindset

768
00:35:13,054 --> 00:35:14,615
that embraces diversity.

769
00:35:14,615 --> 00:35:18,797
And that means digging deep into a company culture

770
00:35:18,797 --> 00:35:21,359
and embedding values and frameworks of thought

771
00:35:21,359 --> 00:35:24,221
when it comes to diversity seamlessly into it.

772
00:35:24,221 --> 00:35:28,263
Diversity is more like a model that matures over time

773
00:35:28,263 --> 00:35:30,605
and taking shortcuts in order to increase head counts

774
00:35:30,605 --> 00:35:31,925
or improve quotas.

775
